Several factors can prevent changes to cable length from being saved. First, ensure you're working within a transaction. EPLAN uses a transaction model to manage changes, and without a transaction, modifications won't be committed. Use `Eplan.EplApi.DataModel.TransactionManager.StartTransaction()` and `Eplan.EplApi.DataModel.TransactionManager.CommitTransaction()` to wrap your code. Second, verify that the cable object is not write-protected. Check the `WRITEPROTECTED` property of the cable. If it's true, you'll need to temporarily disable write protection or work with a copy of the object. Third, make sure you're accessing the correct cable object. Double-check that you're using the correct device tag or object ID to retrieve the cable. Finally, ensure you're using the correct unit for the length value. The unit should match the project's unit settings for length. Here's an example:

```csharp
using Eplan.EplApi.DataModel;
using Eplan.EplApi.Base;

// Assuming you have a cable object 'cable'
using (TransactionManager.StartTransaction("Change Cable Length"))
{
    try
    {
        // Get the property
        PropertyValue propertyValue = cable.Properties.GetPropertyValue(FUNC_CABLELENGTH);

        // Check if the property exists
        if (propertyValue != null)
        {
            // Set the new length (e.g., 10 meters)
            propertyValue.Value = new Decimal(10.0);

            // Commit the transaction
            TransactionManager.CommitTransaction();
            MessageBox.Show("Cable length updated successfully.");
        }
        else
        {
            MessageBox.Show("FUNC_CABLELENGTH property not found.");
        }
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        // Rollback the transaction in case of an error
        TransactionManager.CancelTransaction();
        MessageBox.Show("Error updating cable length: " + ex.Message);
    }
}
```

This example demonstrates the correct way to modify the cable length, including transaction management and error handling. Remember to replace `cable` with your actual cable object.

