There are several reasons why setting the ARTICLE_PLCTYPE property might fail. First, ensure you're using a valid part number and that the part exists in the parts database. Second, verify that you have the necessary write permissions for the part and the project. Third, and most common, is that you are not using a transaction. EPLAN uses a transaction model to manage changes.  Without a transaction, changes are not saved.  Here's a C# example:

```csharp
using Eplan.EplApi.Base;
using Eplan.EplApi.MasterData;

// Assuming you have a valid part number and MDAnyPropertyId for ARTICLE_PLCTYPE
string partNumber = "YourPartNumber";
MDAnyPropertyId articlePlcTypeId = new MDAnyPropertyId(22105); // ARTICLE_PLCTYPE
string plcType = "Siemens S7-1200";

using (new TransactionManager().CreateTransaction("Set PLC Type"))
{
    try
    {
        MDPartsDatabaseItemPropertyList partProperties = new MDPartsDatabaseItemPropertyList();
        MDPartsDatabaseItem part = partProperties.GetPart(partNumber);

        if (part != null)
        {
            partProperties.Property(articlePlcTypeId).Set(plcType);
            // Or, using the MDPartsDatabaseItem overload:
            // partProperties.Property(part, articlePlcTypeId).Set(plcType);
        }
        else
        {
            MessageBox.Show("Part not found.");
        }
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        MessageBox.Show("Error setting PLC Type: " + ex.Message);
        // Rollback the transaction if an error occurs
        TransactionManager.CancelTransaction();
        return;
    }

    // Commit the transaction if everything is successful
    TransactionManager.CommitTransaction();
}
```

Also, check for any exceptions during the process, as they can prevent changes from being saved. If you're working with indexed properties, make sure the index is valid. Finally, verify that the part is not locked by another user or process.

