The `CreateTransient` method creates a segment object in memory, but it doesn't automatically place it on a page.  You need to explicitly set the `Page` property of the segment and then call `TopologyService.UpdatePage()` or `TopologyService.UpdateTopologySegment()` to make the segment visible and update its start and end points.  Without these steps, the segment exists only in the data model, not in the graphical representation.  Also, ensure that the `SymbolReference` objects passed to `CreateTransient` are valid and refer to existing symbols in your project.  Here's a basic example:

```csharp
using Eplan.EplApi.DataModel;
using Eplan.EplApi.HEServices;
// ... inside your script
Project project = ...; // Get your project
Page page = ...; // Get your page
SymbolReference startSymbol = ...; // Get your start symbol reference
SymbolReference endSymbol = ...; // Get your end symbol reference

Segment segment = new Segment();
segment.CreateTransient(project, startSymbol, endSymbol);
segment.Page = page;

TopologyService topologyService = new TopologyService();
topologyService.UpdatePage(page);
```

The `EndPoint` and `StartPoint` properties of a `Segment` are not automatically updated when you modify the `EndSymbolReference` or `StartSymbolReference` properties. This is by design to optimize performance and avoid unnecessary calculations. To update the `EndPoint` and `StartPoint` properties after changing the symbol references, you must call either the `UpdatePage()` or `UpdateTopologySegment()` method of the `TopologyService` class.  `UpdatePage()` updates all segments on a specific page, while `UpdateTopologySegment()` updates a specific segment.  Choose the method that best suits your needs.  For example:

```csharp
using Eplan.EplApi.DataModel;
using Eplan.EplApi.HEServices;
// ... inside your script
Segment segment = ...; // Get your segment
SymbolReference newEndSymbol = ...; // Get your new end symbol

segment.EndSymbolReference = newEndSymbol;

TopologyService topologyService = new TopologyService();
topologyService.UpdateTopologySegment(segment);
```

Also, keep in mind that these methods may throw exceptions if there are issues with the project or the symbol references.  Always include proper error handling in your scripts.

While the documentation specifically mentions `pProject` as a potential cause, a `System.ArgumentNullException` during `CreateTransient` can also be triggered by other null parameters, specifically `pStartSymbol` or `pEndSymbol`. Double-check that both `pStartSymbol` and `pEndSymbol` are valid `SymbolReference` objects and are not null before calling the `CreateTransient` method. Also, ensure that the `SymbolReference` objects are properly initialized and refer to existing symbols within the project.  It's a good practice to add null checks for all parameters before calling any EPLAN API method to prevent unexpected exceptions and improve the robustness of your scripts.  For example:

```csharp
using Eplan.EplApi.DataModel;
// ... inside your script
Project project = ...; // Get your project
SymbolReference startSymbol = ...; // Get your start symbol
SymbolReference endSymbol = ...; // Get your end symbol

if (project == null || startSymbol == null || endSymbol == null)
{
    // Handle the null parameters (e.g., log an error, exit the script)
    return;
}

Segment segment = new Segment();
segment.CreateTransient(project, startSymbol, endSymbol);
```

Yes, you can simplify the process of creating segments, especially when connecting corners, by leveraging the `CreateTransient` method and the `TopologyService.UpdatePage()` method.  The key is to create the segments and set their properties in a more streamlined manner.  Here's a more concise approach for connecting multiple corners:

