Yes, you should definitely use a transaction when modifying multiple properties of a function (or any other data model object) in your EPLAN API script. The primary reason is to ensure data integrity and atomicity. A transaction groups a set of operations into a single, indivisible unit. If any operation within the transaction fails, the entire transaction is rolled back, and all changes are discarded, leaving the project in a consistent state. This prevents partial updates and data corruption.

Without a transaction, if your script modifies several properties and an error occurs in the middle of the process (e.g., a file access issue, a validation error), some properties might be updated while others are not. This can lead to inconsistent data and unpredictable behavior in EPLAN. Using a transaction guarantees that either all property changes are applied successfully, or none of them are. This is especially important when dealing with complex operations or when multiple users might be working on the same project simultaneously. Here's a code example:
```csharp
using (Transaction transaction = new TransactionManager().CreateTransaction())
{
    try
    {
        // Modify function properties
        function.Properties[Properties.Function.FUNC_NAME] = "New Name";
        function.Properties[Properties.Function.FUNC_DESCRIPTION] = "New Description";
        // ... more property modifications

        // Commit the transaction
        transaction.Commit();
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        // Rollback the transaction if an error occurs
        transaction.Abort();
        // Log the error
        Console.WriteLine("Error modifying function: " + ex.Message);
    }
}
```
In this example, if an exception occurs during the property modifications, the `transaction.Abort()` call ensures that all changes are reverted, and the project remains consistent.

